body:
### Version

Yosys 0.58+86 (git sha1 8bc63ef6d, clang++ 18.1.8 -fPIC -O3)

### On which OS did this happen?

Linux

### Reproduction Steps

```verilog
// top.v
module top(input clk, input resetn, output reg r);
  always @(posedge clk or negedge resetn) begin
    if (!resetn) r <= 1'b1;
    else r <= 1'b0;
  end
endmodule
```

```
/* cell.lib */
library(demo) {
  cell(INV) {
    area: 3;
    pin(A) { direction: input; }
    pin(Y) { direction: output;
              function: "!A"; }
  }
  cell(DFFRQN) {
    area: 18;
    ff(IQN, IQNN) { clocked_on: "CK";
                    next_state: "!D";
                    preset : "!RN"; }
    pin(CK) { direction: input;
                 clock: true; }
    pin(D)  { direction: input; }
    pin(RN) { direction: input; }
    pin(QN) { direction: output;
              function: "IQN"; }
  }
}
```

According to the manual of the standard cell, the cell description of `DFFRQN` is
```
D Flip-Flop with Async Clear, Single Output QN
QN = !RN ? 1 : rising(CK) ? !D : pre_QN
```

```
# yosys.tcl
yosys -import
read_verilog -sv top.v
synth -top top
dfflibmap -liberty cell.lib
write_verilog -noattr -noexpr -nohex -nodec netlist.v
```

### Expected Behavior

For reference, below is the netlist generated by commercial synthesis tool. When `resetn` is valid, `n6` is `1`, and `r` is `1`. This is consistent with the original verilog code.

```verilog
module top ( clk, resetn, r );
  input clk, resetn;
  output r;
  wire   n6, n3;

  DFFRQN r_reg ( .D(1'b1), .CK(clk), .RN(resetn), .QN(n6) );
  INV U5 ( .A(n6), .Y(n3) );
  INV U6 ( .A(n3), .Y(r) );
endmodule
```

### Actual Behavior

When `resetn` is valid, `_0_` is `1`, and `r` is `0`. This conflicts with the original verilog code.

```verilog
/* Generated by Yosys 0.58+86 (git sha1 8bc63ef6d, clang++ 18.1.8 -fPIC -O3) */

module top(clk, resetn, r);
  input clk;
  wire clk;
  input resetn;
  wire resetn;
  output r;
  wire r;
  wire _0_;
  \$_NOT_  _1_ (
    .A(_0_),
    .Y(r)
  );
  DFFRQN _2_ (
    .CK(clk),
    .D(1'b0),
    .QN(_0_),
    .RN(resetn)
  );
endmodule
```

